# Sanity Schema Conventions

## Schema categories

| Directory                    | Purpose                           | Examples                      |
|------------------------------|-----------------------------------|-------------------------------|
| `schemas/documents/`         | Top-level document types          | `page`, `siteSettings`        |
| `schemas/modules/`           | Page section types (in modules[]) | `hero`, `pricing`, `finalCta` |
| `schemas/objects/`           | Reusable field groups             | `cta`, `seo`, `theme`        |

## Creating a new module

1. Create `src/sanity/schemas/modules/<name>.ts` using `defineType` + `defineField`
2. Add `themeField()` from `objects/theme.ts` as the first field (default: `"cream"`, `"dark"`, or `"white"`)
3. Export from `schemas/modules/index.ts`
4. Register in `schemas/index.ts` under the Modules section
5. Add `{ type: "<name>" }` to the `modules` array in `schemas/documents/page.ts`
6. Create matching React component in `src/components/modules/<Name>.tsx`
7. Add case to `ModuleRenderer.tsx` switch statement
8. Run `pnpm typegen` to regenerate types

## Theme field

Use the `themeField()` helper for consistent theme options:

```ts
import { themeField } from "../objects/theme";
// themeField("dark") — sets default; options are "dark", "white", "cream"
```

## Singleton documents

`siteSettings` is a singleton with `_id: "siteSettings"`. The Studio structure forces a single document view for it. Query with `*[_id == "siteSettings"][0]`.

## TypeGen workflow

```bash
pnpm typegen          # extract schema + generate sanity.types.ts
```

- Queries in `src/sanity/queries.ts` use `defineQuery()` from `groq`
- Types are re-exported: `export type { PAGE_QUERY_RESULT } from "../../sanity.types"`
- After any schema change, re-run typegen and deploy schema

## Schema deployment

After schema changes, deploy to Sanity cloud so MCP and Studio work correctly:

```bash
nvm use
pnpm dlx sanity@latest schema deploy
```

See `docs/sanity-mcp-troubleshooting.md` for known issues.
